Officials look to security after Brea statue is stolen
The Associated Press
Article Launched: 05/19/2007 04:54:26 PM PDT

BREA, Calif.- City officials are looking for better ways to secure public art after a landmark statue was stolen from a street corner near a school.

"Spirit of Life," a bronze sculpture depicting a mother swinging her child, was taken April 20 after standing 11 years near an elementary school. It was the second piece of public art in Brea taken in a decade.

The theft has prompted officials to consider more high-tech security options including a global positioning system.

"I've been researching and looking for things that we could offer owners such as a LoJack or a GPS system," said Trinitee Manuel, community services specialist for art in public places.

Manuel said she suspects the 350-pound statue worth $85,000 was eventually melted down and cashed in for a few hundred dollars.

In 1996, the Arbors Housing Association commissioned Scottish artist John Kennedy to sculpt the statue. Association president Art Willis said he hopes a replacement sculpture will be up by the end of the year.

"We will absolutely look into higher security," he said.

Brea is city of 35,000 residents about eight miles north of Anaheim. 

